The migration preserves all existing test structure and logic while converting to pytest conventions. **Key Changes:** - Removed `unittest.TestCase` inheritance from all test classes (`TestBSON`, `TestCodecOptions`, `TestDatetimeConversion`, `TestLongLongToString`) - Converted ~100+ unittest assertions to pytest equivalents: - `self.assertEqual(a, b)` ‚Üí `assert a == b` - `self.assertRaises(Exception, func, args)` ‚Üí `with pytest.raises(Exception): func(args)` - `self.assertTrue(x)` ‚Üí `assert x` - And many more assertion patterns - Converted `@unittest.skip` to `@pytest.mark.skip` - Converted custom assertion methods (`assertInvalid`, `round_trip_pickle`) to standalone utility functions - Removed `unittest.main()` block - Updated imports to use `pytest` instead of `unittest` The migration maintains the existing test class structure and organization while adopting pytest conventions. Pytest successfully discovers 86 out of 87 tests (1 skipped), indicating the conversion syntax is correct. ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **Run tests locally and verify they execute and pass** - Most critical since I encountered environment issues preventing full test execution verification - [ ] **Spot-check assertion conversions for correctness** - High volume of mechanical conversions increases risk of logical errors - [ ] **Verify qcheck integration still works** - The `qcheck.check_unittest` calls were updated but may need further adjustment - [ ] **Test broader test suite for regressions** - Ensure the migration doesn't break other tests that might depend on unittest patterns - [ ] **Review custom assertion function conversions** - Check that `assert_invalid` and `round_trip_pickle` functions work identically to original methods --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TB testbson["test/test_bson.py

comment.body:
I think where it's failing to compile for you is 
```
framework:
    type: esp-idf
```
needs to be 
```
framework:
    type: arduino
```
Currently there some arduino specific things being used, which I do want to get around in the future to make it more flexible.

But right now something has changed in ESPHome 2025.7.x where it this integration is broken anyway. The data coming in on the serial port is no longer timed/buffered as it once was, and the Actron uses timed messages. I have an idea how to fix it, first step was to add more robustness and it works a bit now, which is the last commit. Second step to try is to implement another faster task using xTaskCreate to capture the serial data quicker. For now I'm leaving my instance it at `esphome/esphome:2025.6` until I have time to work on it. Maybe even changing the code to work with esp-idf could fix it.

pull_request.title: Elevate Topic Content Experience
pull_request.body:
This commit introduces several new features to significantly enhance the user experience of the Belize travel map, addressing the goal of elevating the "wow factor".

The key enhancements include:

- **Dynamic Constellation Background:** A new `constellations.js` file creates a subtle, animated starfield background. When a location is selected, it draws "constellation" lines connecting it to other related points of interest, reinforcing the "elemental journey" theme.

- **Interactive Filtering:** Users can now filter locations by category (All, Ruins, Nature, Marine) using a new set of filter buttons at the top of the page. This allows for a more focused exploration of the map.

- **Keyboard Navigation:** The map now supports keyboard navigation. Users can cycle through the visible locations using the left and right arrow keys, providing a more fluid browsing experience.

- **Enriched Content Panel:**
    - A new "Atmosphere" section has been added to each location, providing a poetic, thematic description to enhance the narrative.
    - A subtle parallax effect has been added to the panel image, making it feel more dynamic as the user scrolls the content.

- **Data Enrichment:** The location data has been updated with `type_category` for filtering and the new `atmosphere` text.

These changes are integrated cleanly into the existing application structure, building upon the original design philosophy to create a more immersive, interactive, and informative journey.

# Migrate web search to OpenAI Responses API (gpt-5) and remove SerpAPI ## Summary This PR completely migrates the finance agent benchmark from using SerpAPI for web search to using OpenAI's Web Search API via the Responses API with the `gpt-5` model. The migration touches multiple core components: - **Complete replacement of SerpAPI integration** in `GoogleWebSearch` tool with OpenAI Responses API calls - **Added Responses API support** in the LLM abstraction layer (`llm.py`) with automatic detection for `openai/gpt-5` - **Updated agent orchestration** (`agent.py`) to handle the different response format from Responses API - **Removed SerpAPI dependency** from requirements and environment setup - **Added context threading** using `previous_response_id` parameter for conversation continuity The key architectural change is that when using `openai/gpt-5`, the agent bypasses traditional tool calling and instead relies on the model's built-in web search capabilities through the Responses API. ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human ‚ö†Ô∏è **High Risk Changes - 5 Critical Items to Verify:** - [ ] **End-to-end functionality test**: Run `python run_agent.py --questions "What was Apple's revenue in 2023?" --model openai/gpt-5` with a real OpenAI API key to verify web search actually works - [ ] **Response parsing validation**: Check that the JSON parsing logic in `GoogleWebSearch._execute_search()` correctly handles various response formats from the Responses API, including the URL extraction fallback - [ ] **Backward compatibility**: Test that existing models (e.g., `openai/gpt-4o-2024-08-06`) still work correctly and weren't broken by the LLM layer changes - [ ] **Context threading verification**: Run a multi-turn conversation with `gpt-5` to ensure `previous_response_id` is correctly maintained across turns - [ ] **Environment setup**: Confirm that only `OPENAI_API_KEY` is required for `gpt-5` model and no `SERP_API_KEY` is needed **Recommended Test Plan**: Set up a clean environment, install dependencies, set only `OPENAI_API_KEY`, then test both `gpt-5` and a traditional model with the same question to compare results and ensure both code paths work. --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TD RA["run_agent.py"]:::context GA["get_agent.py"]:::minor-edit Agent["agent.py"]:::major-edit LLM["llm.py"]:::major-edit Tools["tools.py"]:::major-edit Req["requirements.txt"]:::minor-edit README["README.md"]:::minor-edit RA --> GA GA --> Agent GA --> Tools Agent --> LLM Agent --> Tools Tools -.-> |"Removed SerpAPI

# Replace SerpAPI with OpenAI Web Search API using Responses API ## Summary This PR migrates the finance agent from using SerpAPI for web search to OpenAI's new Web Search API via the Responses API with the gpt-5 model. The key architectural change is that web search is now handled entirely by OpenAI's backend rather than making external API calls to SerpAPI. **Major Changes:** - **tools.py**: Replaced `GoogleWebSearch` class with `OpenAIWebSearch` class that works with Responses API - **llm.py**: Added `_responses_api_chat()` method to use `client.responses.create()` for gpt-5 with web search tools - **agent.py**: Updated `get_tool_definitions()` to return `{"type": "web_search_preview"}` format for gpt-5 - **get_agent.py**: Updated imports and tool mapping from `google_web_search` to `web_search_preview` - **requirements.txt**: Removed `google-search-results` SerpAPI dependency - **README.md**: Updated documentation to reflect OpenAI web search instead of SerpAPI - **run_agent.py**: Fixed argument parser to accept `web_search_preview` instead of `google_web_search` ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human ‚ö†Ô∏è **CRITICAL**: This implementation has **not been tested end-to-end** due to missing OpenAI API key. The following items are essential to verify: - [ ] **Test web search functionality**: Run `python run_agent.py --questions "What is the current stock price of Apple?" --model openai/gpt-5 --tools web_search_preview` with valid OpenAI API key - [ ] **Verify Responses API integration**: Confirm that `client.responses.create()` calls work correctly and return proper `output_text` with web search results - [ ] **Test response format conversion**: Validate that the mock `ChatCompletion` objects created in `_convert_responses_to_chat_completion()` work with the agent loop - [ ] **Check backward compatibility**: Ensure other models (Claude, etc.) still work correctly with existing Chat Completions API - [ ] **Verify complete SerpAPI removal**: Search codebase for any remaining references to `SERP_API_KEY`, `GoogleWebSearch`, or SerpAPI imports **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. Set `OPENAI_API_KEY` environment variable 2. Test with gpt-5 model and web search queries 3. Test with non-gpt-5 models to ensure no regressions 4. Verify web search results are properly formatted and cited 5. Test error scenarios (invalid queries, API failures) --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TB tools["tools.py

# Add OpenAI Responses API support with web search tool substitution

## Summary

This PR modifies the finance AI agent benchmark to use the OpenAI Responses API when running against OpenAI models, as requested. The key changes include:

- **Tool substitution**: Automatically replaces `google_web_search` (SERP API) with `web_search_preview` (OpenAI's built-in web search) for OpenAI models
- **API switching**: Uses `client.responses.create()` instead of `client.chat.completions.create()` for OpenAI models  
- **Turn completion**: Handles `type: final` messages from Responses API instead of "FINAL ANSWER:" pattern matching
- **Backward compatibility**: Non-OpenAI models continue using the existing implementation unchanged

The tool substitution is transparent to users - they can still specify `"google_web_search"` in the tools parameter and it will automatically map to `"web_search_preview"` for OpenAI models.

## Review & Testing Checklist for Human

- [ ] **Test end-to-end with actual OpenAI model** (e.g., `openai/gpt-4o`) to verify Responses API integration works correctly with web search
- [ ] **Verify tool substitution** - confirm that specifying `google_web_search` in tools parameter gets mapped to `web_search_preview` for OpenAI models
- [ ] **Test turn completion** - verify that conversations end properly when receiving `type: final` messages from Responses API
- [ ] **Verify backward compatibility** - test with non-OpenAI models (e.g., Anthropic) to ensure existing functionality is preserved
- [ ] **Check web search execution** - confirm that web search is handled automatically by Responses API without manual tool execution

**Recommended test command**: 
```bash
python run_agent.py --questions "What was Apple's revenue in 2023?" --model openai/gpt-4o
```

# Use OpenAI Web Search via Responses API for gpt-5; keep SerpAPI for other models ## Summary This PR implements OpenAI Web Search integration for the `openai/gpt-5` model via the Responses API, while maintaining backward compatibility with SerpAPI for all other models. When using `gpt-5`, the agent now leverages OpenAI's built-in web search capability instead of making local SerpAPI calls through the `GoogleWebSearch` tool. **Key Changes:** - **llm.py**: Added Responses API support for gpt-5 with `web_search` tool, updated response parsing and tool call handling - **agent.py**: Modified to handle gpt-5's different response format and skip local tool call processing - **get_agent.py**: Skip `GoogleWebSearch` instantiation when using gpt-5 - **README.md**: Updated documentation to clarify when SERP_API_KEY is needed vs when OpenAI Web Search is used ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **Test gpt-5 web search end-to-end** - Verify that `python run_agent.py --questions "What was Apple's revenue in 2023?" --model openai/gpt-5` works without SERP_API_KEY - [ ] **Test backward compatibility** - Ensure other models like `openai/gpt-4o` still work correctly with SerpAPI and SERP_API_KEY - [ ] **Verify response parsing** - Check that gpt-5 responses are correctly parsed (especially the `output_text` attribute assumption) - [ ] **Test error handling** - Ensure graceful failures if Responses API parameters are incorrect or if the service is unavailable - [ ] **Review type safety** - The existing codebase has type issues; verify my changes don't introduce runtime errors **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. Set up environment with OPENAI_API_KEY but no SERP_API_KEY 2. Test gpt-5: `python run_agent.py --questions "Current Bitcoin price" --model openai/gpt-5` 3. Add SERP_API_KEY and test other model: `python run_agent.py --questions "Current Bitcoin price" --model openai/gpt-4o --tools google_web_search` 4.
